,"Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Whyton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Wyton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wyton","meanings":["English:  see  Whitton   (2)."]},{"name":"Whitton","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Whitton in Morebattle (Roxburghshire). The placename is from Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farm, village’, as with many of the places in 2 below.","English: habitational name from any of the places called Whitton (Durham, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Northumberland, Shropshire, Suffolk) or Witton (Cheshire, Durham, Lancashire, Herefordshire, Norfolk, Northumberland, Warwickshire, Worcestershire, North Yorkshire); or possibly from Wyton (Huntingdonshire, East Yorkshire); or possibly from Weeton, Market Weighton, or Little Weighton (East Yorkshire). The placenames do not all share the same etymology but most of their post-medieval spellings are interchangeable. Most of the placenames derive from the Old English personal name <i>Hwīta</i> or Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some, for example Witton in Warwickshire, derive from Old English <i>wīc</i> ‘dwelling, specialized farmstead’ + <i>tūn</i>, and some others, for example Witton in Norfolk, derive from Old English <i>widu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>tūn</i>. Whitton in Lincolnshire derives from the Old English personal name <i>Hwīta</i> (genitive <i>Hwītan</i>) or Old English <i>hwīt</i> (dative <i>hwītan</i>) + <i>ēg</i> ‘island’. Witton in Lancashire derives from the Old English personal <i>Witta</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","English: in Devon, this surname is a variant of   Whiddon  ."]}]},{"name":"Katerine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of   Katherine .  This is a popular form in Russia, which is also occasionally used in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["equivalent of   Katherine  , also occasionally used in the English-speaking world."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":65,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Katerine De Whyton was born about 1390, in England. She married Thomas Whitton about 1405. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in York, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"aproximadamente 1390–":"umbes 1390–Surnud","1384–1440":"1384–1440","1405–1457":"1405–1457","1390–Female":"1390–Surnud","1457":"1457","1455":"1455","aproximadamente 1390":"umbes 1390","1440":"1440","1384":"1384","Abt 1405":"umbes 1405","1390":"1390","1405":"1405","Inglaterra":"England","in York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Oxfordshire, Inglaterra, Reino Unido":"Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"aproximadamente 1390–":"noin 1390–Kuollut","1384–1440":"1384–1440","1405–1457":"1405–1457","1390–Female":"1390–Kuollut","1457":"1457","1455":"1455","aproximadamente 1390":"noin 1390","1440":"1440","1384":"1384","Abt 1405":"noin 1